# AI Agent Instructions

This is a single-user personal workspace. No external audience.
All AI agents operating in this directory tree must follow these instructions.

## Documentation Style

- This workspace has one user — do not write for a broader audience
- All documentation (README, comments, inline docs) must be short and precise
- Prefer code examples over explanations:
  ```
  # bad
  "To run the tests, execute the following command in your terminal"

  # good
  `pytest -x --tb=short`
  ```
- No filler text, no marketing language, no verbose descriptions
- If something is self-evident from code, do not document it

## Language and Communication

- Always communicate in English, regardless of prompt language
- Be direct and technical — the user is an experienced engineer
- Do not over-explain basic concepts
- Ask when uncertain rather than guessing

## General Behavior

- Always use the latest stable version of tools, languages, and frameworks unless explicitly told otherwise
- Preserve existing directory structure and conventions
- Never create files unless strictly necessary — prefer editing existing files
- Never create documentation files (README, etc.) unless explicitly asked
- Do not add emojis unless explicitly requested
- Do not add unnecessary comments to code
- If a task is ambiguous, ask for clarification before proceeding

## Shell and Environment

- Primary shell: nushell
- Scripts must also work in bash and zsh (use POSIX sh where possible)
- direnv is used for per-directory environment setup (`.envrc` files)
- tmuxp is used for tmux session/window management

## Code Style

- Prefer readability over cleverness
- Use consistent naming conventions matching the existing codebase
- Keep functions small and focused
- Use meaningful variable and function names

## Robustness and Error Handling

- Never use broad exception handlers (`except Exception`, bare `except:`) unless explicitly requested by the user for a specific boundary
- Catch only the concrete exception types expected at that call site
- Keep `try` blocks narrow; only wrap statements that can raise the handled exception
- Do not silently swallow failures; log/propagate with enough technical context to debug
- When UI is present, surface runtime failures clearly in the UI with operation context and technical details
- Prefer fail-fast behavior for unexpected states; do not mask programming errors
- Do not duplicate business logic across paths; extract shared helpers/constants and reuse them
- Keep constraints centralized (paths, policies, config keys, feature flags) instead of scattering literals
- Validate inputs and invariants at boundaries, then operate on normalized data internally
- Ensure degraded/fallback behavior is explicit, deterministic, and observable

## File and Directory Conventions

- This workspace contains mixed content: projects, notes, configs, personal data
- Subdirectories may have their own `AGENTS.md` with more specific instructions — those take precedence
- Do not modify files outside the current working scope without explicit permission
- Respect `.gitignore` patterns where present
- Never commit secrets, credentials, or `.env` files

## Git

- Do not commit unless explicitly asked
- Do not push unless explicitly asked
- Follow existing commit message conventions in the repository
- Never force-push to main/master

## Security

- Never expose or log secrets, tokens, API keys, or passwords
- Do not create or modify `.env` files without explicit instruction
- Avoid running destructive commands (rm -rf, DROP TABLE, etc.) without confirmation
